TY  - JOUR
T1  - Option Volume and Stock Prices: Evidence on Where Informed Traders Trade
AU  - Easley, David
AU  - O'Hara, Maureen
AU  - Srinivas, P.S.
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.194060
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 431
EP  - 465
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.194060
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper investigates the informational role of transactions volume in options markets. We develop an asymmetric information model in which informed traders may trade in option or equity markets. We show conditions under which informed traders trade options, and we investigate the implications of this for the linkage between markets. Our model predicts an important informational role for the volume of particular types of option trades. We empirically test our model's hypotheses with intraday option data. Our main empirical result is that negative and positive option volumes contain information about future stock prices.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Conditional Performance of Insider Trades
AU  - Eckbo, B. Espen
AU  - Smith, David C.
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.205263
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 467
EP  - 498
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.205263
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper estimates the performance of insider trades on the closely held Oslo Stock Exchange (OSE) during a period of lax enforcement of insider trading regulations. Our data permit construction of a portfolio that tracks all movements of insiders in and out of the OSE firms. Using three alternative performance estimators in a time-varying expected return setting, we document zero or negative abnormal performance by insiders. The results are robust to a variety of trade characteristics. Applying the performance measures to mutual funds on the OSE, we also document some evidence that the average mutual fund outperforms the insider portfolio.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Nonparametric Estimation of State-Price Densities Implicit in Financial Asset Prices
AU  - Aït-Sahalia, Yacine
AU  - Lo, Andrew W.
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.215228
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 499
EP  - 547
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.215228
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Implicit in the prices of traded financial assets are Arrow?Debreu prices or, with continuous states, the state-price density (SPD). We construct a nonparametric estimator for the SPD implicit in option prices and we derive its asymptotic sampling theory. This estimator provides an arbitrage-free method of pricing new, complex, or illiquid securities while capturing those features of the data that are most relevant from an asset-pricing perspective, for example, negative skewness and excess kurtosis for asset returns, and volatility ?smiles? for option prices. We perform Monte Carlo experiments and extract the SPD from actual S&P 500 option prices.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - On Stable Factor Structures in the Pricing of Risk: Do Time-Varying Betas Help or Hurt?
AU  - Ghysels, Eric
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.224803
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 549
EP  - 573
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.224803
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - There is now considerable evidence suggesting that estimated betas of unconditional capital asset pricing models (CAPMs) exhibit statistically significant time variation. Therefore, many have advocated the use of conditional CAPMs. If we succeed in capturing the dynamics of beta risk, we are sure to outperform constant beta models. However, if the beta risk is inherently misspecified, there is a real possibility that we commit serious pricing errors, potentially larger than with a constant traditional beta model. In this paper we show that this is indeed the case, namely that pricing errors with constant traditional beta models are smaller than with conditional CAPMs.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Resolving the Puzzling Intertemporal Relation between the Market Risk Premium and Conditional Market Variance: A Two-Factor Approach
AU  - Scruggs, John T.
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.235793
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 575
EP  - 603
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.235793
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The existing empirical literature fails to agree on the nature of the intertemporal relation between risk and return. This paper attempts to resolve the issue by estimating a conditional two-factor model motivated by Merton's intertemporal capital asset pricing model. When long-term government bond returns are included as a second factor, the partial relation between the market risk premium and conditional market variance is found to be positive and significant. The paper also helps explain the convoluted empirical relation between the market risk premium, conditional market variance, and the nominal risk-free rate previously reported in the literature.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Block Share Purchases and Corporate Performance
AU  - Bethel, Jennifer E.
AU  - Liebeskind, Julia Porter
AU  - Opler, Tim
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.244195
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 605
EP  - 634
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.244195
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper investigates the causes and consequences of activist block share purchases in the 1980s. We find that activist investors were most likely to purchase large blocks of shares in highly diversified firms with poor profitability. Activists were not less likely to purchase blocks in firms with shark repellents and employee stock ownership plans. Activist block purchases were followed by increases in asset divestitures, decreases in mergers and acquisitions, and abnormal share price appreciation. Industry-adjusted operating profitability also rose. This evidence supports the view that the market for partial corporate control plays an important role in limiting agency costs in U.S. corporations.
ER  - 

