T1  - The Foreign Exchange Exposure of Japanese Multinational Corporations
AU  - He, Jia
AU  - Ng, Lilian K.
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.295575
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 733
EP  - 753
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.295575
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We find that about 25 percent of our sample of 171 Japanese multinationals' stock returns experienced economically significant positive exposure effects for the period January 1979 to December 1993. The extent to which a firm is exposed to exchange-rate fluctuations can be explained by the level of its export ratio and by variables that are proxies for its hedging needs. Highly leveraged firms, or firms with low liquidity, tend to have smaller exposures. Foreign exposure is found to increase with firm size. We also find that keiretsu multinationals are more exposed to exchange-rate risk than nonkeiretsu firms.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Analysis of Bidding in the Japanese Government Bond Auctions
AU  - Hamao, Yasushi
AU  - Jegadeesh, Narasimhan
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.305342
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 755
EP  - 772
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.305342
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We examine the bidding patterns and auction profits in the Japanese Government Bond (JGB) auctions and empirically test the predictions of auction theory. We find that the average profit in JGB auctions is not reliably different from zero, and the degree of competition and the level of uncertainty are insignificant in determining auction profits. The winning shares of the U.S. dealers are positively related to auction profits, whereas the winning shares of their Japanese counterparts show a negative association. We also find that the share of winnings of Japanese dealers tends to be correlated with the share of winnings of their compatriot dealers but a similar relation is not found for U.S. dealers.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Takeovers of Privately Held Targets, Methods of Payment, and Bidder Returns
AU  - Chang, Saeyoung
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.315138
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 773
EP  - 784
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.315138
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We examine bidder returns at the announcement of a takeover proposal when the target firm is privately held. In stock offers, bidders experience a positive abnormal return, which contrasts with the negative abnormal return typically found for bidders acquiring a publicly traded target. On the other hand, bidders experience no abnormal return in cash offers. Our analysis suggests that the positive wealth effect is related to monitoring activities by target shareholders and, to an extent, reduced information asymmetries.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Managerial Ownership, the Method of Payment for Acquisitions, and Executive Job Retention
AU  - Ghosh, Aloke
AU  - Ruland, William
Y1  - 1998/04/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/04/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.325125
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 785
EP  - 798
VL  - 53
IS  - 2
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0022-1082.325125
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This study investigates how acquiring and target firm managers' preferences for control rights motivate the payment for corporate acquisitions. We expect that managers of target firms who value influence in combined firms will prefer to receive stock. One reason top managers desire influence is to enhance their chances of retaining jobs in the combined firm. Our analysis shows a strong, positive association between managerial ownership of target firms and the likelihood of acquisitions for stock. We also find that managers of target firms are more likely to retain jobs in combined firms when they receive stock rather than cash.
ER  - 

